data.description:
We’re happy to announce the Facebook SDK 3.1 for iOS that adds support for the Facebook integration in iOS 6. This integration opens up new opportunities for mobile app developers as you can easily build the foundation for a social app, Facebook Login and sharing functionality, into your product.

Read more about this new release on our blog: https://developers.facebook.com/blog/post/2012/09/25/facebook-sdk-for-ios-and-the-ios-6-facebook-integration/

Developers upgrading from the SDK v3.0 will need to add in three extra framework dependencies ('Accounts', 'AdSupport' and 'Social'), and be aware of how to ask for read and publish permissions, as described on https://developers.facebook.com/docs/getting-started/facebook-sdk-for-ios/3.1/upgrading-from-3.0/

This is also described in the updated "Getting Started" screencast, below. Start developing today to take advantage of these powerful new tools and resources for iOS.

Which has absolutely EVERYTHING in it... 

Every post, every like, every share, every comment, and absolutely every minuscule activity fed to Facebook by the games I play and the apps I use...

Talk about a needle in a haystack...

I refuse to believe it's necessary that Facebook has to be so consistently messed up... All The Freakin' Time... >:(
PPS: 'Allow' and 'Don't Allow' is insufficient... I need to be able to 'Force'  the posts I want displayed on my time line.

I think I figured out the secret way to fix this... first you go to your activity log... find the post you were looking for... then set it to 'highlighted' on your timeline... this ofc will make it huge... taking up the whole width of your timeline... but at least it is ON your timeline... then you go back to your timeline... and click the little 'star' on the post that will 'remove it from highlights' 

Now the post is back on your timeline...

As for how long it will be back...

I have no idea...

 This book was written for thoughtful members of the public.
